🎯 Phishing Awareness Training
🟦 Slide 1: Title

Phishing Awareness Training
Stay Safe. Think Before You Click.

🟦 Slide 2: What is Phishing?

Phishing is a type of cyberattack where attackers try to trick you into sharing sensitive information like:

Passwords
Bank details
OTPs

They pretend to be trusted sources like banks, companies, or even your friends.

🟦 Slide 3: How Phishing Happens

Phishing can come through:

Emails (most common)
SMS (called Smishing)
Phone calls (Vishing)
Fake websites

👉 The goal is always the same: make you act quickly without thinking

🟦 Slide 4: Social Engineering Explained

Phishing works because of human psychology, not technology.

Attackers use:

Urgency: “Act now or your account will be blocked!”
Fear: “Suspicious login detected!”
Greed: “You’ve won ₹10,000!”
Trust: “Message from your boss or bank”
🟦 Slide 5: Types of Phishing
Email Phishing – Fake emails from companies
Spear Phishing – Targeted at a specific person
Whaling – Targets executives
Smishing – SMS scams
Vishing – Phone call scams
🟦 Slide 6: How to Recognize a Phishing Email

Look carefully at:

✅ Sender’s email address

Example: support@paypaI.com
 (fake “l” instead of “l”)

✅ Language

Poor grammar or strange wording

✅ Urgency

“Immediate action required!”

✅ Links

Hover before clicking

✅ Attachments

Unexpected files = danger
🟦 Slide 7: Fake Website Warning Signs
URL looks similar but slightly wrong
No proper security (or fake HTTPS trust)
Poor design or broken layout
Asking for sensitive info immediately

👉 Always type website URLs manually when in doubt

🟦 Slide 8: Real-Life Examples

Example 1: Bank Alert

“Your account is blocked. Click here to verify.”

→ Fake login page steals your password

Example 2: Delivery Scam

“Your package is pending. Pay ₹50.”

→ Leads to fake payment page

Example 3: Job Offer

“You are selected! Pay registration fee.”

→ Scam for money collection

🟦 Slide 9: Best Practices to Stay Safe
Never share passwords or OTPs
Enable Two-Factor Authentication (2FA)
Don’t click unknown links
Verify requests from official sources
Keep your system updated
Use antivirus/security tools
🟦 Slide 10: What To Do If You Suspect Phishing
Don’t click anything
Don’t reply
Report it (IT team or email provider)
Delete the message

If you already clicked:

Change passwords immediately
Check bank accounts
Inform authorities if needed
🟦 Slide 11: Quick Quiz (Interactive)

Q1: What is phishing?
A. Fishing method
B. Cyberattack to steal data ✅
C. Software

Q2: Which is a warning sign?
A. Trusted domain
B. Urgent password request ✅
C. Official logo

Q3: What should you do first?
A. Click link
B. Ignore warning
C. Verify source ✅

Q4: Is HTTPS always safe?
A. Yes
B. No ✅

🟦 Slide 12: Activity – Spot the Scam

Show two emails:

One real
One fake

Ask participants:

Which one is phishing?
What clues helped you decide?
🟦 Slide 13: Key Takeaways

✔ Think before you click
✔ Verify before you trust
✔ Never share sensitive info
✔ Stay alert

🟦 Slide 14: Final Message

Cybersecurity starts with you.
A single click can lead to a big problem — or prevent one.
